The root cause of the null dereference is that `stdscr` is used in `_curses_initscr_impl` without checking if it is NULL. In the code:

```c
if (initialised) {
    wrefresh(stdscr);
    return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
}
```

If `stdscr` is NULL (possibly due to a failed previous initialization or a bug), this will cause a null pointer dereference.

**Patch Plan:**
- Add a check for `stdscr == NULL` in the `if (initialised)` block.
- If `stdscr` is NULL, raise an appropriate Python exception and return NULL.

This will prevent the null dereference and provide a proper Python error.

Let's generate the patch.
```diff
--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -3257,10 +3257,18 @@
     if (initialised) {
-        wrefresh(stdscr);
-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
+        if (stdscr == NULL) {
+            PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, "curses not properly initialized: stdscr is NULL");
+            return NULL;
+        }
+        wrefresh(stdscr);
+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
     }

     win = initscr();

     if (win == NULL) {
         PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, catchall_NULL);
         return NULL;
     }
```

